4o. Let Charity herself Judge, whether that be not impudence in the highest, for a man that is himself a Bishop to call any proceedings in an assembly, especially in a Parlimentary assembly, against Bishops by the name of a Rebellion. And let the Reader iudge, whether you be not the man that speak at this rate, making your self, and all of your Order, Kings and Princes (at least) in these words of yours, p. 13. And therfore if any assembly hath (like Corah) rebelled against Aaron, and cast their Bishops and preachers out of doores: I would advise them to follow the Councell of S
                  t Ambrose in the like case. Quod inconsulto fecerunt, consultius revocetur; what they have inconsiderately done to throw them out, let them more advisedly revoke, and call them in againe. It is an easie matter to discerne for what meridian this Calculation is made; and what assembly it is, that is complained on for rebelling against Aaron, that is, for casting their Bishops and preachers out of doores. I tell you Sir, that all the water in the Sea will never wash you cleane from the guilt of impudence, who being but a single and simple man;

 shall tell such an assembly as the Parliament of England: they have done any thing inconsideratly. Might not the malefactor when he is cast by the Judge at the Barre, with as much modesty, tell the Judge that he knew the law better then he, and that he had given an uniust sentence? But to call that act of this great assembly, whereby they cast their Bishops (for Preachers I believe they cast out none) out of doores, Rebellion, smell's so ranke of the Chayre, that it is enough to fill the whole Kingdome with the stench and ill savour of it; and to move every man to tread and trample upon the Chaire as a snuffe.
